Purpose

This webpage/report is intended to aggregate information from different agencies (i.e. USACE, SFWMD, FWC, USGS and NOAA) into one spot to help inform local government agencies and stakeholders on conditions within Lake Okeechobee, the Northern Estuaries and the Everglades ecosystem. The data provided here should be considered preliminary and are subject to change.

Lake Okeechobee inflow and outflow volume from USACE.


Lake Flows: In the past 7 days the total outflow from Lake Okeechobee was 34,278 AF with 22,659 AF to the Caloosahatchee through S-77, and 11,435 AF to the EAA through S-351, S-352, and S-354. The total net inflow to the Lake was 41,653 AF (41,653 AF from Fisheating Creek, S-71, S-72, S-84s, S-65EX, and S-65EX1) .

Northern Estuaries

Caloosahatchee River Estuary

Discharge Conditions

Daily and 14-day moving average discharge for S-79 relative to the Northern Estuaries RECOVER performance measure for the recent 30-day period.

CRE Discharge Salinity Envelope - 6 months plot

Caloosahatchee Conditions Summary: Flow to the Caloosahatchee Estuary had a 7-day average of 1,932 cfs at S-79 with a 7-day average of 1,506 cfs coming from the lake at S-77. The 14-day moving average flow at S-79 is 1,903 cfs and has been in the optimal flow envelope (750 - 2100 cfs; RECOVER 2020) for 11 days.
